    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-25T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-25T09:00:00-05:00" n="154"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1179: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting Chairman of the American Delegation (<persName
                            corresp="#p_GHS1" type="from">Gibson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-25T15:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 25, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 25—12:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>277. <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">Wilson</persName> and I have had two
                    conversations with <persName corresp="#p_MT1">Matsudaira</persName> and
                        <persName corresp="#p_SNJD1">Sato</persName> in the last few days. They fear
                    that their Government will feel that the worst reduction of fleets bears more
                    heavily on the weaker than on the stronger powers in spite of the unchanged
                    mathematical ratio.</p>
                <p>They had been under the misapprehension that the President’s proposal covered the
                    abolition of land bombardment aviation only and were greatly relieved and
                    interested to learn from us that the prohibition on air bombardment and the
                    abolition of bombers applied equally to naval forces.</p>
                <p>You may feel it wise to apprise the Ambassador in Tokio of this misapprehension
                    as it may be mentioned to him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GHS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
